  "prompt": "Why do some old computer games run very fast on new, powerful computers?",
  "response": "This happens because older computer games were often designed with a fixed frame rate or game speed tied directly to the computer's processor clock speed. Modern computers have much faster processors compared to older machines, so when these games run on new hardware, they execute game logic and rendering much more quickly than originally intended.\n\nIn other words, the game's internal timing mechanism is directly linked to the CPU's speed, so a faster processor means the game runs proportionally faster. This can make the game nearly unplayable because characters move too quickly, animations are sped up, and gameplay becomes extremely rapid.\n\nTo address this issue, developers and enthusiasts have created various solutions like:\n1. Emulation software that can limit processing speed\n2. Game patches that decouple game speed from processor speed\n3. Third-party utilities that can artificially slow down the game\n4. DOSBox (an emulator specifically designed to run old DOS games at more manageable speeds)\n\nThis problem was especially common in games from the late 1980s and early 1990s before developers implemented more sophisticated timing mechanisms that were independent of raw processor speed.",
